```

instead of

```

[{"sha":"c359560ffa7fdd8df121ac30a01bb46ceb8449d0","author":{"name":"Angel Velazquez","email":"e7be62313d96a6aa5d44f8f6bc3f3eab388c04d9@amazon.com"},"message":"Don't return error when logs are discarded in awslogs

Docker logs an error every time the awslogs driver discards a message. Messages
are discarded when the internal awslogs buffer (channel) is full and the driver
is configured in non-blocking mode.
Logging every time a message is discarded can be problematic since Docker logs
can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk space.
Instead, it's preferable to log a warning periodically, displaying the number
of logs discarded for the period.

Compared with before, this will save one op in rewriting.
*Remove the requirement that `element_shape`'s all dimensions must be known.
*Only match the pattern when the first dimension of the tensorlist is known.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: I9c3dc67a9ae50652950a666bc270ecb5c1162f28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/cb647c4213b32d2e3a54e82cc0a2efe1708bca31"},{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

The placeholders attributes is just a string, but importing it as StringAttr
is losing the original type information and prevent proper roundtripping.

Here is the doc in the protobuf definition for this type:

    // This is a placeholder only used in nodes defined inside a
    // function.  It indicates the attr value will be supplied when
    // the function is instantiated.  For example, let us suppose a
    // node "N" in function "FN". "N" has an attr "A" with value
    // placeholder = "foo". When FN is instantiated with attr "foo"
    // set to "bar", the instantiated node N's attr A will have been
    // given the value "bar".

[{"sha":"2d73a89abd691173fc3410cd66f9938813d05ea7","author":{"name":"Angel Velazquez","email":"e7be62313d96a6aa5d44f8f6bc3f3eab388c04d9@amazon.com"},"message":"Don't return error when logs are discarded in awslogs

Docker logs an error every time the awslogs driver discards a message. Messages
are discarded when the internal awslogs buffer (channel) is full and the driver
is configured in non-blocking mode.
Logging every time a message is discarded can be problematic since Docker logs
can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk space.

Change-Id: I3bff11f33e901e6e64f192ec279fc31729a44265","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/c51709e5dba6e94eea9d3c5bbe892a2d7a48b7cf"},{"sha":"6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Fuse chain of tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output, tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output and tf.Identity ops in same island.

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

Only one D2H or H2D copy can be running at one time, so if the compute stream
does even a small D2H copy, it can block for a long time.  We can do better by
using pinned memory, which is readable and writable on both the CPU and GPU.

Change-Id: I3bff11f33e901e6e64f192ec279fc31729a44265","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/c51709e5dba6e94eea9d3c5bbe892a2d7a48b7cf"},{"sha":"6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Fuse chain of tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output, tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output and tf.Identity ops in same island.

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368225681
Change-Id: Ic3559e3b2e823ab59ed32a52484c394af52cb78b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/497ebaf698834b42b3f3819e86384ba407429f4a"},{"sha":"f66782631d276c390732a513cdef6ad91eb4e779","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:Python][PJRT] Only link in Cloud TPU initializer if building for TPU.

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: I9c3dc67a9ae50652950a666bc270ecb5c1162f28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/cb647c4213b32d2e3a54e82cc0a2efe1708bca31"},{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/9ca3bb632ecea1530be0286f7d23ca6f3f32c4a6"},{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Unlike resources, we do not need to capture marked paths here, so we
just discard the marks.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/9c580335e303610f96e01cfa8859ea6ee78ea87e"},{"sha":"4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"terraform: Hide maybe-sensitive provisioner output

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

Core was previously ignoring JSON-encoded dynamic values, but these are
technically supported, so we must either error or accept the value.
Since we already have the decoder for Json state, it's minimal effort to
support this on all plugin methods too.

This change also gives providers an easy way to implement the
UpgradeResourceState method. The obvious implementation of returning the same
JSON-encoded value has tripped up a few providers not using the legacy
SDK already, and we should have at least indicated that the value was
being lost.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e"},{"sha":"98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26606 from hashicorp/jbardin/proposed-set-comparison

More precise handling of lists and maps within sets for ProposedNewObject","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb"},{"sha":"30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/cliconfig: Allow development overrides for providers

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were

[{"sha":"5f5432e8ea443daa1a77eb9abd65445d3583f6c8","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: v0.15 upgrade guide for sensitive resource attributes (#28355)

* website: v0.15 upgrade guide for sensitive resource attributes

Our earlier draft of this guide didn't include a section about the
stabilization of the "provider_sensitive_attrs" language experiment. This
new section aims to address the situation where a module might previously
have been returning a sensitive value without having marked it as such,
and thus that module will begin returning an error after upgrading to
Terraform v0.15.

As part of that, I also reviewed the existing documentation about these
features and made some edits aiming to make these four different sections
work well together if users refer to them all at once, as they are likely
to do if they follow the new links from the upgrade guide. I aimed to
retain all of the content we had before, but some of it is now in a new
location.

In particular, I moved the discussion about the v0.14 language experiment
into the upgrade guide, because it seems like a topic only really relevant
to those upgrading from an earlier version and not something folks need to
know about if they are using Terraform for the first time in v0.15 or
later.

* minor fixups

Co-authored-by: Kristin Laemmert <mildwonkey@users.noreply.github.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/5f5432e8ea443daa1a77eb9abd65445d3583f6c8"}]

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745"},{"sha":"47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remote provisioners require a connection config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e"},{"sha":"2b252ac677f1d99adcf08202c3047be2478a1055","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27910 from hashicorp/jbardin/remote-provisioners

This isn't incredibly important, but Kitchen-Terraform is written in and requires tests to be written in Ruby.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/f172585eaa23b9edc40c5b73b066654e1bae7120"},{"sha":"54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: A better error message for custom variable validation

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

Change-Id: I3bff11f33e901e6e64f192ec279fc31729a44265","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/c51709e5dba6e94eea9d3c5bbe892a2d7a48b7cf"},{"sha":"6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Fuse chain of tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output, tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output and tf.Identity ops in same island.

Earlier v1 island coarsening only considered tf.TPUReplicatedInput/Output ops to be fused in island cluster if the producer/consumers are within the cluster. This change expands it to also consider tf.TPUPartitionedInput/Output. Sometimes there may also be tf.Identity ops in between these ops which must also be fused in the same island.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368189129
Change-Id: I2c369ce73f69d67b4f0ba8c62b836ade40045016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/6a278b9cf2fbed781661079b13d88b4106622a09"},{"sha":"fc94423b490e0dc4530f334d4a58c76132a14170","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Support the input/output data type inside the mlir quantizer

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

Change-Id: Ic3559e3b2e823ab59ed32a52484c394af52cb78b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/497ebaf698834b42b3f3819e86384ba407429f4a"},{"sha":"f66782631d276c390732a513cdef6ad91eb4e779","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:Python][PJRT] Only link in Cloud TPU initializer if building for TPU.

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

[{"sha":"99c69f0853423c62b9b07e71dcc7a6163afa3b04","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix sloppy factoring when assigning finishedLanes

`finishedLanes` is assigned in `performSyncWorkOnRoot` and
`performSyncWorkOnRoot`. It's meant to represent whichever lanes we
used to render, but because of some sloppy factoring, it can sometimes
equal `NoLanes`.

The fixes are:
- Always check if the lanes are not `NoLanes` before entering the work
loop. There was a branch where this wasn't always true.
- In `performSyncWorkOnRoot`, don't assume the next lanes are sync; the
priority may have changed, or they may have been flushed by a
previous task.
- Don't re-assign the `lanes` variable (the one that gets assigned to
`finishedLanes` until right before we enter the work loop, so that it
is always corresponds to the newest complete root.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/99c69f0853423c62b9b07e71dcc7a6163afa3b04"}]

* Add format context

* Let the Work node hold all working state for the recursive loop

Stacks are nice and all but there's a cost to maintaining each frame

* Synchronously render children of a Suspense boundary

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

This patch added an MLIR pass to modify the input and output types of the
models. This is based on the assumption that the input models have leading
tfl.quantize ops and tailing tfl.dequantize ops. The modification uses the
following rules:

- Requested float input type: no input change
- Requested int8 input type: remove the tfl.quantize op
- Requested uint8 input type: change the input storage type of the tfl.quantize op from int8 to uint8
- Requested float output type: no input change
- Requested int8 output type: remove the tfl.dequantize op
- Requested uint8 output type: replace the tfl.dequantize op by an tfl.quantize op and change the output storage type uint8

Change-Id: Ic3559e3b2e823ab59ed32a52484c394af52cb78b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/497ebaf698834b42b3f3819e86384ba407429f4a"},{"sha":"f66782631d276c390732a513cdef6ad91eb4e779","author":{"name":"Skye Wanderman-Milne","email":"4c878c1ae364587078acae22009e8542fed717b6@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:Python][PJRT] Only link in Cloud TPU initializer if building for TPU.

With this change,
tensorflow/core/tpu/tpu_executor_dlsym_initializer.cc is only linked
in if --define=with_tpu_support bazel=tpu is passed to bazel. This is
so jaxlib can be built on Windows by not including linux-only TPU
dependencies (https://github.com/google/jax/issues/5985).

I previously tried separating out all of the PJRT TPU dependencies,
but this caused problems in libraries that assume TPU support is
always linked in (namely chex).

Change-Id: I9c3dc67a9ae50652950a666bc270ecb5c1162f28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/cb647c4213b32d2e3a54e82cc0a2efe1708bca31"},{"sha":"45901fcb824e014d5fd1c911acb4b75b91ad6946","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Collect Python garbage on every jit call.

We suspect that more eager garbage collection is needed to avoid some OOM behavior in our CI tests where tests use large NumPy arrays.

Make garbage collection for arbitrary Python objects (e.g., buffers) more eager, while keeping garbage collection of traceback objects more lazy to limit the benchmark impact.

`jit_simple_dispatch` is neutral:

```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%   9.8µs ± 5%  -2.01%  (p=0.005 n=19+19)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  10.0µs ± 7%              9.8µs ± 4%  -1.86%        (p=0.009 n=19+19)
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

[{"sha":"5543d9e2964b949bed2a03e3b5d4b68068a430e9","author":{"name":"Kristin Laemmert","email":"30cb4a936f196f8da41f6469d07b31397d334edc@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: v0.15 upgrade guide for sensitive resource attributes (#28355) (#28365)

* website: v0.15 upgrade guide for sensitive resource attributes

Our earlier draft of this guide didn't include a section about the
stabilization of the "provider_sensitive_attrs" language experiment. This
new section aims to address the situation where a module might previously
have been returning a sensitive value without having marked it as such,
and thus that module will begin returning an error after upgrading to
Terraform v0.15.

As part of that, I also reviewed the existing documentation about these
features and made some edits aiming to make these four different sections
work well together if users refer to them all at once, as they are likely
to do if they follow the new links from the upgrade guide. I aimed to
retain all of the content we had before, but some of it is now in a new
location.

In particular, I moved the discussion about the v0.14 language experiment
into the upgrade guide, because it seems like a topic only really relevant
to those upgrading from an earlier version and not something folks need to
know about if they are using Terraform for the first time in v0.15 or
later.

* minor fixups

Taking the same approach as was taken in containerd

The new library has a slightly different output;

- keys at the same level are sorted alphabetically
- empty sections not omitted (`proxy_plugins`, `stream_processors`, `timeouts`),
  which could possibly be be addressed with an "omitempty" in containerd's struct.
- empty slices are not omitted (`imports`, `required_plugins`)

This test has been flaky for a long time, failing with:

    --- FAIL: TestInspect (12.04s)
        inspect_test.go:39: timeout hit after 10s: waiting for tasks to enter run state. task failed with error: task: non-zero exit (1)

While looking through logs, noticed tasks were started, entering RUNNING stage,
and then exited, to be started again.

    state.transition="STARTING->RUNNING"
    ...
    msg="fatal task error" error="task: non-zero exit (1)"
    ...
    state.transition="RUNNING->FAILED"

Looking for possible reasons, first considering network issues (possibly we ran
out of IP addresses or networking not cleaned up), then I spotted the issue.

The service is started with;

    Command:         []string{"/bin/top"},
    Args:            []string{"-u", "root"},

The `-u root` is not an argument for the service, but for `/bin/top`. While the
Ubuntu/Debian/GNU version `top` has a -u/-U option;

    docker run --rm ubuntu:20.04 top -h 2>&1 | grep '\-u'
      top -hv | -bcEHiOSs1 -d secs -n max -u|U user -p pid(s) -o field -w [cols]

The *busybox* version of top does not:

    docker run --rm busybox top --help 2>&1 | grep '\-u'

So running `top -u root` would cause the task to fail;

    docker run --rm busybox top -u root
    top: invalid option -- u
    ...

    echo $?
    1

As a result, the service went into a crash-loop, and because the `poll.WaitOn()`
was running with a short interval, in many cases would _just_ find the RUNNING
state, perform the `service inspect`, and pass, but in other cases, it would not
be that lucky, and continue polling untill we reached the 10 seconds timeout,
and mark the test as failed.

Looking for history of this option (was it previously using a different image?) I
found this was added in 6cd6d8646a90fa2013416bc8f11bd78d72c4180d, but probably
just missed during review.

Given that the option is only set to have "something" to inspect, I replaced
the `-u root` with `-d 5`, which makes top refresh with a 5 second interval.

Note that there is another test (`TestServiceListWithStatuses) that uses the same
spec, however, that test is skipped based on API version of the test-daemon, and
(to be looked into), when performing that check, no API version is known, causing
the test to (always?) be skipped:

    === RUN   TestServiceListWithStatuses
        --- SKIP: TestServiceListWithStatuses (0.00s)
            list_test.go:34: versions.LessThan(testEnv.DaemonInfo.ServerVersion, "1.41")

Earlier we sorted ops from the first op merged into the island and any of the special TPU outputs ops that would be present at the end of the vector of islands to be merged. Note that it did not consider the order between special TPU output ops. It can lead to failure if two consecutive special TPU output ops are added to the island vector out of order.

This change adds documentation as to why the sorting is required and does it between the first island merged and the last island in the block that was merged.

Earlier we sorted ops from the first op merged into the island and any of the special TPU outputs ops that would be present at the end of the vector of islands to be merged. Note that it did not consider the order between special TPU output ops. It can lead to failure if two consecutive special TPU output ops are added to the island vector out of order.

This change adds documentation as to why the sorting is required and does it between the first island merged and the last island in the block that was merged.

Change-Id: I8b5b52d668bc6ddc1d47267dcdbef199617f5a7f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/333aa3d41647c2a7bc14f3d61f456ce47ed9a0a7"},{"sha":"a2aa3750c37738fb73bb46606b017f8478428dde","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Modify v1 island coarsening to sort islands between first op and last op merged into the island cluster.

Earlier we sorted ops from the first op merged into the island and any of the special TPU outputs ops that would be present at the end of the vector of islands to be merged. Note that it did not consider the order between special TPU output ops. It can lead to failure if two consecutive special TPU output ops are added to the island vector out of order.

This change adds documentation as to why the sorting is required and does it between the first island merged and the last island in the block that was merged.

[{"sha":"1f4ad17f423a8924a9c64b49f8e5cece21556832","author":{"name":"Jeremy Meredith","email":"e623f03c87c36e14fb66e36c2983621bef758449@google.com"},"message":"Updating output arguments for experimental C++ ops to list each individually.

The immediate benefit is that each output argument has a caller-visible name in the signature.  In turn, this makes it easier to use named variables in the calling code (see nn_grad_test.cc).

Additionally, it removes the caller requirement on container types for non-list arguments.

This simplifies some calling logic as well, using C arrays to give compiler length hints, allowing simpler notation in some cases (e.g. {initializer_list} instead of MakeSpan()), and avoids the (harder-to-read) subspan() calls.  This also avoids the heap for these temporary tensor handle pointer allocations.

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

[{"sha":"1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871","author":{"name":"Michal Rostecki","email":"82ebf970c69340aebb770c3853be5fd96a3eb584@opensuse.org"},"message":"btrfs: Do not disable quota on cleanup

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")
Signed-off-by: Michal Rostecki <mrostecki@opensuse.org>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dgkh1975/moby/commits/1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871"},{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

[{"sha":"1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871","author":{"name":"Michal Rostecki","email":"82ebf970c69340aebb770c3853be5fd96a3eb584@opensuse.org"},"message":"btrfs: Do not disable quota on cleanup

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")
Signed-off-by: Michal Rostecki <mrostecki@opensuse.org>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871"},{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

[{"sha":"1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871","author":{"name":"Michal Rostecki","email":"82ebf970c69340aebb770c3853be5fd96a3eb584@opensuse.org"},"message":"btrfs: Do not disable quota on cleanup

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")
Signed-off-by: Michal Rostecki <mrostecki@opensuse.org>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JonathanSimon123/moby/commits/1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871"},{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

[{"sha":"1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871","author":{"name":"Michal Rostecki","email":"82ebf970c69340aebb770c3853be5fd96a3eb584@opensuse.org"},"message":"btrfs: Do not disable quota on cleanup

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")
Signed-off-by: Michal Rostecki <mrostecki@opensuse.org>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871"},{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

[{"sha":"1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871","author":{"name":"Michal Rostecki","email":"82ebf970c69340aebb770c3853be5fd96a3eb584@opensuse.org"},"message":"btrfs: Do not disable quota on cleanup

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")

[{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745"},{"sha":"47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remote provisioners require a connection config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e"},{"sha":"2b252ac677f1d99adcf08202c3047be2478a1055","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27910 from hashicorp/jbardin/remote-provisioners

This isn't incredibly important, but Kitchen-Terraform is written in and requires tests to be written in Ruby.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/f172585eaa23b9edc40c5b73b066654e1bae7120"},{"sha":"54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: A better error message for custom variable validation

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

Earlier we sorted ops from the first op merged into the island and any of the special TPU outputs ops that would be present at the end of the vector of islands to be merged. Note that it did not consider the order between special TPU output ops. It can lead to failure if two consecutive special TPU output ops are added to the island vector out of order.

This change adds documentation as to why the sorting is required and does it between the first island merged and the last island in the block that was merged.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Mark packages with layering_check violations.

This is a no-op for OSS builds because currently we do not use layering_check.

Support for the layering_check feature has been added to bazel's autoconfig cc_toolchain (see https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/pull/11440), but TensorFlow uses custom toolchains for most builds. We might enable layering_check sometime in the future.

Google-internal builds traditionally disabled layering_check for cuda-adjacent code. This change is a preparation for enabling it.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/77096349e185923ff64f1c5dcf38a3c8d10a11b6"},{"sha":"e4cf1c733677ff77e51101e2de542373b449b471","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"pull: use tag service for pulling tagged reference

The tag service does a `HEAD` request to get the manifest digest, where
we can then do a `GET` against the digest.

The `GET` by tag is not cacheable, but the `GET` against the digest is.
This allows proxies to work way better.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/e4cf1c733677ff77e51101e2de542373b449b471"},{"sha":"c208f03fbddb4355729c3225bb2550c4d54a2c5e","author":{"name":"Cuong Manh Le","email":"54b4457f1dff6823379654eb5867596497ba782f@gmail.com"},"message":"pkg/devicemapper: fix invalid usage of reflect.SliceHeader

The current usage of reflect.SliceHeader violates rule 6th of
unsafe.Pointer conversion. In short, reflect.SliceHeader could not be
used as plain struct.

See https://golang.org/pkg/unsafe/#Pointer

dockerd currently does not support containerd on Windows, so this does
not store manifests on Windows, yet.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/9ca3bb632ecea1530be0286f7d23ca6f3f32c4a6"},{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Signed-off-by: Tibor Vass <tibor@docker.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tnir/moby/commits/beff0a5f2c62e655260c09697680c25a3e9a7ce1"},{"sha":"05c20a6e1c708bc881dee36554c6598937afa699","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"handleContainerExit: put a timeout on containerd DeleteTask

Also move c.Lock() below containerd delete task, as it doesn't seem that
there is any necessity to hold the container lock while containerd is
killing the task.

This fixes a potential edge-case where containerd delete task hangs, and
thereafter all operations on the container would hang forever, as this
function is holding onto the container lock.

[{"sha":"a2aa3750c37738fb73bb46606b017f8478428dde","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Modify v1 island coarsening to sort islands between first op and last op merged into the island cluster.

Earlier we sorted ops from the first op merged into the island and any of the special TPU outputs ops that would be present at the end of the vector of islands to be merged. Note that it did not consider the order between special TPU output ops. It can lead to failure if two consecutive special TPU output ops are added to the island vector out of order.

This change adds documentation as to why the sorting is required and does it between the first island merged and the last island in the block that was merged.

[{"sha":"1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871","author":{"name":"Michal Rostecki","email":"82ebf970c69340aebb770c3853be5fd96a3eb584@opensuse.org"},"message":"btrfs: Do not disable quota on cleanup

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")
Signed-off-by: Michal Rostecki <mrostecki@opensuse.org>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bai/moby/commits/1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871"},{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

[{"sha":"1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871","author":{"name":"Michal Rostecki","email":"82ebf970c69340aebb770c3853be5fd96a3eb584@opensuse.org"},"message":"btrfs: Do not disable quota on cleanup

Before this change, cleanup of the btrfs driver (occuring on each daemon
shutdown) resulted in disabling quotas. It was done with an assumption
that quotas can be enabled or disabled on a subvolume level, which is
not true - enabling or disabling quota is always done on a filesystem
level.

That was leading to disabling quota on btrfs filesystems on each daemon
shutdown.

This change fixes that behavior and removes misleading `subvol` prefix
from functions and methods which set up quota (on a filesystem level).

Fixes: #34593
Fixes: 401c8d176743 ("Add disk quota support for btrfs")
Signed-off-by: Michal Rostecki <mrostecki@opensuse.org>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/1ec689c4c2ecda24ed8495451c53072bb0497871"},{"sha":"8e362b75cb8cfbc539169cbb5d77c52802f65eb1","author":{"name":"Cam","email":"1041179cbdda366fd7b0347f09255f775170e103@sparr.email"},"message":"docker daemon container stop refactor

this refactors the Stop command to fix a few issues and behaviors that
dont seem completely correct:

1. first it fixes a situation where stop could hang forever (#41579)
2. fixes a behavior where if sending the
stop signal failed, then the code directly sends a -9 signal. If that
fails, it returns without waiting for the process to exit or going
through the full docker kill codepath.
3. fixes a behavior where if sending the stop signal failed, then the
code sends a -9 signal. If that succeeds, then we still go through the
same stop waiting process, and may even go through the docker kill path
again, even though we've already sent a -9.
4. fixes a behavior where the code would wait the full 30 seconds after
sending a stop signal, even if we already know the stop signal failed.

fixes #41579

Change-Id: I8b5b52d668bc6ddc1d47267dcdbef199617f5a7f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/333aa3d41647c2a7bc14f3d61f456ce47ed9a0a7"},{"sha":"a2aa3750c37738fb73bb46606b017f8478428dde","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Modify v1 island coarsening to sort islands between first op and last op merged into the island cluster.

Earlier we sorted ops from the first op merged into the island and any of the special TPU outputs ops that would be present at the end of the vector of islands to be merged. Note that it did not consider the order between special TPU output ops. It can lead to failure if two consecutive special TPU output ops are added to the island vector out of order.

This change adds documentation as to why the sorting is required and does it between the first island merged and the last island in the block that was merged.

Change-Id: I8b5b52d668bc6ddc1d47267dcdbef199617f5a7f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/333aa3d41647c2a7bc14f3d61f456ce47ed9a0a7"},{"sha":"a2aa3750c37738fb73bb46606b017f8478428dde","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Modify v1 island coarsening to sort islands between first op and last op merged into the island cluster.

Earlier we sorted ops from the first op merged into the island and any of the special TPU outputs ops that would be present at the end of the vector of islands to be merged. Note that it did not consider the order between special TPU output ops. It can lead to failure if two consecutive special TPU output ops are added to the island vector out of order.

This change adds documentation as to why the sorting is required and does it between the first island merged and the last island in the block that was merged.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 368512382
Change-Id: Ie4ef251c3d2f210c3fa962470d7edf9cc68d7b33","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/6ffcdab5375b919742b1e425980bd043b2115cae"},{"sha":"1f4ad17f423a8924a9c64b49f8e5cece21556832","author":{"name":"Jeremy Meredith","email":"e623f03c87c36e14fb66e36c2983621bef758449@google.com"},"message":"Updating output arguments for experimental C++ ops to list each individually.

The immediate benefit is that each output argument has a caller-visible name in the signature.  In turn, this makes it easier to use named variables in the calling code (see nn_grad_test.cc).

Additionally, it removes the caller requirement on container types for non-list arguments.

This simplifies some calling logic as well, using C arrays to give compiler length hints, allowing simpler notation in some cases (e.g. {initializer_list} instead of MakeSpan()), and avoids the (harder-to-read) subspan() calls.  This also avoids the heap for these temporary tensor handle pointer allocations.

* Add NewContext module

This implements a reverse linked list tree containing the previous
contexts.

* Implement recursive algorithm

This algorithm pops the contexts back to a shared ancestor on the way down
the stack and then pushes new contexts in reverse order up the stack.

* Move isPrimaryRenderer to ServerFormatConfig

This is primarily intended to be used to support renderToString with a
separate build than the main one. This allows them to be nested.

* Wire up more element type matchers

* Wire up Context Provider type

* Wire up Context Consumer
